# JavaScript Conventions

Target: ES2022+. Cloudflare Workers, vanilla frontend, scripts.

## Basics

- `const` by default. `let` when reassignment required. Never `var`.
- Arrow functions for callbacks. Named `function` declarations at top level.
- Template literals over string concatenation.
- `async/await` over raw Promise chains.
- ESM everywhere (`import`/`export`). No CommonJS in new code.

## Errors

All async errors handled explicitly. No unhandled rejections.

```js
async function fetchResource(url) {
  const response = await fetch(url)
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error(`fetch ${url}: ${response.status}`)
  }
  return response.json()
}
```

No silent `catch` blocks. Log or rethrow.

## Cloudflare Workers

```js
export default {
  async fetch(request, env, ctx) {
    const url = new URL(request.url)
    // route by url.pathname
  }
}
```

- Secrets via `env.SECRET_NAME`, not hardcoded.
- KV `get` returns `null` on miss — check explicitly.
- No Node.js-only APIs (`fs`, `path`, `crypto` with Node semantics).

## Validation

Validate all inputs at entry. Bound lengths, ranges, and types.

```js
function processItems(items) {
  if (!Array.isArray(items) || items.length > MAX_ITEMS) {
    throw new Error(`items must be array, max ${MAX_ITEMS}`)
  }
}
```

## JSDoc for Public APIs

```js
/**
 * @param {string} id
 * @returns {Promise<{name: string, email: string}>}
 */
async function getUser(id) { ... }
```

## Testing

Vitest. Test behavior, not implementation. Error paths explicitly covered.

## Tiger Style

- All loop iterations over user data have explicit bounds checks.
- No floating promises — await or attach a handler.
